     <h5>William Castellana: South Williamsburg Street Portraits </h5> 
     <h6>January – June 2015</h6> 
     <h3>Castellana's photo series features street scenes and portraits of Hasidic Jewish famililes currently living in the South Williamsburg neighborhood of Brooklyn, New York </h3> 
     <p><img src="images/william-castellana_williamsburg_boysholdinghands.jpg" alt="BoysHoldingHands" width="500" height="330" class="img_dont_wrap"></p> 
     <p><em>Boys Holding Hands / Beford Avenue, Williamsburg, Brooklyn</em>. Courtesy of William Castellana. </p> 
     <p>&nbsp;</p> 
     <p><em>William Castellana: South Williamsburg Street Portraits</em> is now on view in our second floor gallery! Castellana's photo series features street scenes of the South Williamsburg neighborhood in Brooklyn, New York, which is home to many Yiddish-speaking Hasidic Jewish families. </p> 
     <p>Castellana is also a resident of South Williamsburg, and he takes these photographs quickly and unposed. The results offer a candid glimpse into the daily lives of South Williamsburg's Hasidic residents as they live in the midst of a flurry of gentrification taking over the Williamsburg neighborhood. </p> 
     <p>In the past 15 years, North Williamsburg has undergone a gentrification due, in part, to large-scale re-zoning along Williamsburg’s waterfront – luring up-and-coming young professionals as well as investors and celebrity residents to the neighborhood. South Williamsburg, in stark contrast, has experienced almost no urban renewal and remains an anachronism; traditional concepts of community and family are widely held amongst the Yiddish-speaking Hasidic residents. </p> 
     <p>At the turn of the 21st century, about 7,000 Hasidic families were living in South Williamsburg. Hasidim place a high value on family; couples marry young and raise large families. Secular education is secondary to religious training, which has contributed to unemployment and poverty. </p> 
     <p>In Castellana's images we find the tensions and contrasts between the often boisterous and well-healed Williamsburg residents, and the simple, home-centered lives of the Hasidic families.</p> 
     <p>William Castellana photographed these street images between November 2013 and November 2014. This exhibition includes 30 photographs selected from the 70 pictures in the series. </p> 
     <p>&nbsp;</p> 
